{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.15,0.06,0.55,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1155"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93282"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45188"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a slowly enlarging, painless neck lump. She has experienced 5 kg of unintentional weight loss over the past 12 months and increasing fatigue. She has no difficulty swallowing or breathing. She migrated from the Philippines six months ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm erythematous, non-tender lymph node in the right anterior cervical chain (Image). The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 13.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 465 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate: 36 mm/hr (\u0026lt;30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excisional biopsy of the lymph node","Magnetic resonance imaging of the neck","Blood cultures","Fine needle aspiration of the lymph node","Antistreptolysin O titre"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of cervical tuberculous lymphadenitis: chronic lymphadenopathy, constitutional symptoms, and migration from a tuberculosis-endemic country. The raised inflammatory markers and normal chest X-ray are consistent with extra-pulmonary tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E of the lymph node is the most appropriate initial investigation. It is minimally invasive and can provide diagnostic material for cytology, acid-fast bacilli staining, and mycobacterial culture. The sensitivity and specificity for diagnosing tuberculous lymphadenitis are high when all these tests are combined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E of the lymph node would provide definitive tissue diagnosis but is unnecessarily invasive as a first-line investigation. It may be considered if fine needle aspiration is non-diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the neck may demonstrate the extent of lymphadenopathy but cannot provide a tissue diagnosis. It would not be the next most appropriate test as the diagnosis requires histological confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are unlikely to be helpful in this case as mycobacterial bacteraemia is rare, and the patient is clinically stable without signs of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntistreptolysin O titre\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose post-streptococcal conditions. It would not be helpful in this case as the clinical presentation is not consistent with streptococcal infection or its sequelae.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical tuberculous lymphadenopathy is the most common form of extra-pulmonary tuberculosis and should be suspected in immigrants from endemic areas.","Fine needle aspiration is the initial diagnostic test of choice for suspected tuberculous lymphadenitis.","Constitutional symptoms and raised inflammatory markers support the diagnosis of tuberculous lymphadenitis."],"references":["Deveci HS, Kule M, Kule ZA, Habesoglu TE. Diagnostic challenges in cervical tuberculous lymphadenitis: A review. North Clin Istanb. 2016 Sep 28;3(2):150-155. doi: 10.14744/nci.2016.20982. PMID: 28058405; PMCID: PMC5206468.","Jha BC, Dass A, Nagarkar NM, Gupta R, Singhal S. Cervical tuberculous lymphadenopathy: changing clinical pattern and concepts in management. Postgrad Med J. 2001 Mar;77(905):185-7. doi: 10.1136/pmj.77.905.185. PMID: 11222827; PMCID: PMC1741959."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93282"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18047"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18047"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/66bf652c-a675-4219-9761-f8f2000b8f43.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/66bf652c-a675-4219-9761-f8f2000b8f43.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93282"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T19:37:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T19:38:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1155"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"se